<h2>What Is the International Satellite Cloud Climatology Project (ISCCP)?</h2>

<p>
The <A href="/describe/overview.html">International Satellite Cloud Climatology Project (ISCCP)</A> was established in 1982 as part of the <A href="http://wcrp.wmo.int">World Climate Research Program (WCRP)</A> to collect weather satellite radiance measurements and to analyze them to infer the global distribution of clouds, their properties, and their diurnal, seasonal and interannual variations. The resulting <A href="/products/onlineData.html">datasets and analysis products</A> are being used to study the <A href="/role.html">role of clouds in climate</A>, both their effects on <A href="AtSurRadFlx.html">radiative energy exchanges</A> and their role in the <A href="EvapCldPrec.html">global water cycle.</A></p>

<p>
The ISCCP cloud datasets provide our first systematic global view of cloud behavior of the space and time scales of the weather yet covering a long enough time period to encompass several El Ni&#241;o - La Ni&#241;a cycles. Below is a single global snap-shot of clouds.</p>

<div style="width:440px" class="floatcenter">
<img src="isccp_famous.gif" style="width:440px;height:260px;border:0" alt="Sample ISCCP global map of clouds" />
</div>


